node.text: Sopes are rounds of griddled masa with a little rim around the edge to hold delicious fillings. “In my house, sopes were always filled with refried black beans, pulled chicken, chopped romaine lettuce, crema, crumbled fresh cheese, and then one or two salsas and guacamole or avocado to top,” writes Epi contributor @Fanygerson. But sopes are made to be customized, she says. Learn the cooking method in the video above, and check out the link in our bio to get the recipe.

node.text: Gorditas are one of the most popular street foods in Mexico. According to @fanygerson, the translation means “little fatties,” and they’re thick masa pockets that are toasted on a comal, then stuffed with fillings. Watch the video to learn all of Gerson’s tips and tricks, then click the link in our bio for the recipe—and a sweet variation, too.

node.text: You can find tlacoyos all across Mexico—and they’re one of @fanygerson’s favorite street food snacks. The thick oval-shaped masa patties are crispy on the outside, stuffed with beans or other fillings, and piled high with a refreshing cactus salad. Here, Fany shows you how to make them, step by step, to devour right away or stock your freezer. Read more and get the recipe at the link in our bio.

node.text: “For many families, making tamales is a ritual, and younger and older generations each have specific roles in the process,” writes Epi contributor, chef @fanygerson. Here, Gerson walks you through the whole method, step by step, so you can make the fluffiest, most flavorful tamales of your life. Read more and get the recipe at the link in our bio.

node.text: When chef and cookbook author Fany Gerson (@fanygerson) first moved to New York from Mexico over 20 years ago, it wasn’t a matter of *wanting* to find good tortillas—she *needed* them. Mass-produced tortillas from supermarkets and delis had nothing in common with the supple, fragrant fresh tortillas she knew and loved in Mexico. So she started making her own—now she’s here to share her tips, step by step. Read more and get the recipe at the link in our bio. Director: @c.emanuelsmith DP: @bendewster Editor: @elliottjchrist

node.text: One day, you will be in a market, and you will pass the coconuts. They will grab your attention. You'll say to yourself, "I'm going to buy this coconut." You settle at the register, and bring your groceries home. You put most of them away. As you hold up that last item, you will ask yourself: "Why did I buy this coconut?" At least we can help answer how to open it!

node.title: 50 People Try to Crack Open a Coconut

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on September 13, 2021. May be an image of drink.

node.text: When life gives you pineapple rinds, make tepache! Just like the rich cuisine of Mexico, this homestyle, low-ABV drink appears in different regional variations—but a common recipe includes pineapple rinds for a subtly sweet finished product that's just as at home in a cocktail as it is served simply over ice. Learn more about tepache—including how to make it—from Epi contributor Paola Briseño-González (@paolasuavicrema) at the link in bio. Recipe enriqueolveraf Photo @j_deleo, Food Styling @curlygirlcooks

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on September 13, 2021. May be an image of food.

node.text: Summer isn't quite over, fall hasn't officially begun: Welcome to pre-fall, arguably one of the most glorious seasons for cooking. The markets are still offering up summery ingredients, but the temperatures are now cool enough to contemplate turning on the oven. From slow-cooked green beans to baked tomatoes with toast, grab the 13 recipes we're making right now at the link in bio. Photo @j_deleo, Prop Styling @hedgehedge, Food Styling @simoncooks

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on September 12, 2021. May be an image of text.

node.text: Autumn is just around the corner and you know what that means: It's blockbuster cookbook season! Just in time to help you beat pandemic cooking fatigue, this new crop of cookbooks brings you 30-minute meals, celebrity chef-driven tomes, and plenty of vegetarian and vegan offerings. Read all about our 63 picks at the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on September 11, 2021. May be an image of dessert.

node.text: Two things make this chocolate cake shine. First, chocolate pyramids (ethically sourced and designed by @ldvega in collaboration with industrial designer Remy Labesque) melt into gooey puddles of chocolate that'll make you say, "Chocolate chips, who?" Second, the last of your late summer zucchini crept into this bake to give it a moist, pillowy texture that beautifully complements the rich chocolate and crunchy walnuts. Learn more about why you need chocolate pyramids in your life and grab the recipe for chocolate zucchini cake at the link in bio. Recipe, Photo and Food Styling @pithzester

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on September 11, 2021. May be an image of food and indoor.

node.text: It's good to be green—green rice, that is. Take a generous amount of herbs, some salty almonds, lime, and garlic and pulse it into a pesto-like sauce in a food processor. Toss that with rice (or any grain of your choice), then pair with fresh, end-of-summer tomatoes and hard-boiled eggs for this Easiest Week Ever classic from former Epi Digital Director @davidtamarkin. Photo @j_deleo, Food Styling, @acstockwell

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on September 10, 2021. May be an image of food.

node.text: Our Easiest Week Ever continues with this 30-minute pot of pure comfort food from cookbook author Chetna Makan (@chetnamakan). You'll combine split moong dal with a generous mix of aromatics. Then you'll add spinach, buzz with your immersion blender, and swirl yogurt into that vibrant green mixture. It's so simple but so satisfying. The only decision you have to make: bread, rice—or both? Get the recipe at the link in bio. Photo @j_deleo, Food Styling @kaitlinwayne

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on September 10, 2021. May be an image of food, indoor and text that says 'FOOR HUGGERS FOOD'.

node.text: Want to stop wasting your fresh produce? Even with the best storage solutions, it's easy to forget that last bit of bell pepper or half-used sweet potato. That’s why we're in love with these reusable silicone discs that can wrap around just about any kind of produce—and keep it fresh for days. They're compact, easy to wash, and, well, just smart! Find even more reasons to swoon over these food savers at the link in our bio. Photo @travis.rainey

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on September 09, 2021. May be an image of food.

node.text: Get ready to meet your new go-to trick for cooking flawless salmon: Cube it! No, really. Epi and BA staffer Tiffany Hopkins (@itsiffypop) reviewed this recipe for yogurt-marinated spiced salmon in no uncertain terms: "It’s the easiest salmon I’ve ever cooked: perfectly charred along the edges and flaky and tender within." Get the recipe from chef and cookbook author Sabrina Ghayour (@sabrinaghayour) from the link in bio. Photo and Food Styling @j_deleo

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on September 09, 2021. May be an image of food.

node.text: A 10-minute dinner that you can eat with your hands is an Easiest Week Ever must. This creamy, herby dip ties together a handful of ingredients for a full meal, and it’s just as good shared among friends for a park picnic as it is at home for a simple supper. Former Epi editor Anna Stockwell (@acstockwell) says you can save even more time on this simple recipe by steaming your beans and shrimp up to a day ahead. Same goes for the sauce, but you may need to make a double batch—it's that good. Photo @chelsealouisekyle, Prop Styling @sophiestrangio, Food Styling @monicapierini

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on September 08, 2021. May be an image of pasta.

node.text: "Melted" broccoli forms the base for this wallet-friendly recipe that's a rarity: a pasta dish you haven't made before. Former Epi staffer and cookbook author Sheela Prakash (@sheela.m.prakash) packs this simple dinner with layers of flavor using the humblest of pantry ingredients (anchovies! capers! breadcrumbs!) that clocks in at under $8 to make. Ready to melt? Grab the recipe at the link in our bio. Photo @kteig

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on September 08, 2021. May be an image of food.

node.text: Our Easiest Week Ever continues with breakfast for dinner. This puffy, golden apple and cheddar Dutch baby from cookbook author Jenna Helwig (@jennahelwig) is just the thing to get you through midweek. It only needs a few ingredients that you likely already have on hand and comes together in one pan in about 30 minutes. What are you waiting for? Grab the recipe at our link in bio. Photo @j_deleo, Food Styling @kaitlinwayne

node.text:
Creamy-cool, buttery, and topped with citrus zest for an aromatic finish, this frozen avocado cake is an incredibly refreshing dessert to enjoy during the last days of summer. 

"Adding sweetened condensed milk to the crust gives this cake a candy-like texture that reminds me of a Twix bar,” says cookbook author Nadine Levy Redzepi (@nadinelevyredzepi). 
You’ll be tempted to dig in immediately, but be sure to let the cake stand at room temperature for 10 to 15 minutes before slicing. Get the recipe at the link in bio. Photo and Food Styling @kendrakendrakendra
